<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-572-824  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 572 824.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  August 28 1989 v6 n34 p17(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Graphics design package adds polygon processing. (McDonnellDouglas Information Systems' Graphic Design System) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smalley, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   McDonnell Douglas Corp. McDonnell Douglas Information Systems Co.andO;(product enhancement).andO;Product:   Graphics Design System (computer graphics software) (productenhancement).andO;Topic:     Geographic Information SystemsModelingGraphics SoftwareEnhancements.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Graphics Design Package Adds Polygon ProcessingandM;ST.andP;  LOUIS -- Officials from McDonnell Douglas Information Systems haveannounced the addition of polygon processing capabilities to their GraphicsDesign System (GDS) software, designed for geographic information systems andfacilities management systems.andM;GDS incorporates an object-based spatial database management system and runson VAXstations as well as workstations from Tektronix of Wilsonville, Ore.andM;Polygon processing is accomplished through the polygon-chain-node (PCN)Spatial Modeling System.andP;  This system facilitates spatial analysis andmodeling capabilities for topologically structured databases, according tocompany officials.andM;PCN supports polygons, chains and nodes as topological data structures, theofficials said.andM;Chains are linear data structures.andP;  &quot;Chains can intersect with other chainsand can be adjacent to polygons.andP;  Some examples would be a stream bed, asewer or a roadway,&quot; a company spokesman said.andM;In this context, nodes refer to physical or analytical features such as roador sewer intersections, according to the spokesman.andM;PCN also provides an interactive spaghetti processor that organizes data thatwas put into the system in a confusing format, such as data scanned from amap, the spokesman said.andM;Underlying IntelligenceandM;PCN is part of a topological system that provides the underlying intelligenceof the graphical representations.andM;&quot;All of that information can be tied in to a spatially consistent system.andP;  Itprovides integrity to the graphical information you see,&quot; the spokesman said.andM;The company has not yet scheduled a release date for GDS with the PCN SpatialModeling System.andM;Prices range from $12,000 to $58,000, depending on configuration.andP;  Some ofthe configurations are for turnkey systems that include the VAXstationplatform.andM;For additional information, McDonnell Douglas Information Systems Co. can becontacted at 11330 Olive St., Suite 220, St. Louis, MO 63141-7107, (314)872-3122.andO;</TEXT></DOC>